In terms of our current work about T-CDs and previous work about PVK-CDs, a conclusion can be deduced that the passivation method based on free radical polymerization has no dependence on the groups on the surface of conventional CDs and is able to give CDs various properties and functions by desirable monomers. The passivation layer not merely contributes to fluorescence enhancement of CDs but also introduces heteroatoms and functional groups for advanced applications. The comparative results between passivation method based on free radical polymerization and other traditional covalent methods are listed in Table 3
                        . Most passivation methods either relies on specific groups between CDs and coupling agents or requires several steps of a long time and a harsh temperature for coupling reactions. Conversely, free radical polymerization as a feasible and universal passivation method are free of the worries above (Fig. 6
                        ).
